         <abstract>
            <p>In many situations traders may be keen to place caps or floors on aggregate price risks of ongoing transactions over finite time periods. In such circumstances, hedging strategies involving ordinary options and futures may not be satisfactory and other contracts may be desirable. These contracts are path-dependent contracts whose payouts are based on the average price and are encountered in over-the-counter markets. The economic role and valuation of these contracts are examined, and these contracts are contrasted with strategies involving ordinary options.</p>
         </abstract>
